              "title": "Fingertip Impedance",
              "shortDescription": "The mechanical responsiveness of the finger to environmental disturbances.",
              "description": "Mechanical impedance is a frequency-dependent measure of a system's resistance to motion. It is defined as the ratio of force to velocity: F/V. For a robot finger, it is measured using a dynamometer, which excites the fingertip with sinusoidal motions while measuring the resulting contact force. From the data, the frequency response of the mechanical impedance is measured, and dynamic properties are extracted by fitting a model to the data. For a passive (uncontrolled) finger, the effective mass, stiffness, and damping can be extracted. For controlled fingers, bounds on the controlled mass, stiffness, and damping can be determined. The fingers' passive dynamics define the system resonance, which imposes a fundamental limitation on force bandwidth both from the actuators to the environment and from the environment to the actuators.",
